>> ### Geometric Sequences ### <<

"Geometric" sequences can be recognized by their pattern of repeated multiplication. For example, [`a = \left \{ 1, \dfrac{1}{2}, \dfrac{1}{4}, \dfrac{1}{8}, \dots \right \} `] is a _geometric_ sequence because each term is [`\dfrac{1}{2}`] of the term preceding it. In this situation, [`\dfrac{1}{2}`] is called the "_common ratio_":  
* *ratio* because it refers to the division of consecutive terms in the sequence;  
* and *common* because _all_ pairs of consecutive terms (in a _geometric_ sequence) have the same ratio.

Any sequence that has the pattern of the "common ratio" is called a _geometric_ sequence.

